The paper focuses on developing a multi-GPU graph processing library for scalable performance on large graphs with billions of edges. This involves analyzing theoretical and practical limits to scalability, optimizing traversal and memory allocation, and achieving best-of-class performance across operations and datasets. 

Based on these factors, the most likely sub-category is cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing), which deals with the design, analysis, and implementation of algorithms and systems for distributed and parallel computing. 

The next likely sub-category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), which deals with the design, analysis, and implementation of efficient data structures and algorithms for various applications. 

cs.DB (Databases) is also a likely sub-category, as the paper deals with processing large graphs and optimizing memory allocation, which are relevant to database systems. 

cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) is another possible sub-category, as the paper involves analyzing theoretical and practical limits to scalability and optimizing performance for numerical computations. 

Finally, cs.LG (Machine Learning) is a less likely sub-category, as the paper does not explicitly mention machine learning, but the optimization techniques and performance analysis may be relevant to machine learning applications.
